      <hedline>
        <hl1>Is Faith Too Dominant?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Elliott Kipnis letter, commenting on August 17 article on speech by Democratic vice presidential running mate Sen Joseph I Lieberman at Democratic National Convention, expresses concern over Democrats' seeming lack of concern for concept of separation of church and state</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lieberman Sets Stage for Gore as Democrats Seal the Ticket''  (front page, Aug. 17), about Senator Joseph I. Lieberman's speech at the Democratic National Convention:</p>
        <p>I am troubled by the excessive references to faith and God in the Democratic campaign. What happened to the separation of church and state?</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Lieberman Sets Stage for Gore as Democrats Seal the Ticket''  (front page, Aug. 17), about Senator Joseph I. Lieberman's speech at the Democratic National Convention:</p>
        <p>I am troubled by the excessive references to faith and God in the Democratic campaign. What happened to the separation of church and state?</p>
        <p>Is a person who is not actively involved in organized expressions of religious faith uninterested in the welfare of his or her community, or any less moral than a person who attends organized religious services? Is an atheist necessarily unqualified for public office? The tenor of both the Republican and Democratic campaigns seems to suggest so.</p>
        <p>The upcoming debate should not be about which party is the more pious, but rather about which party's philosophy and policies are in our best national interest.</p>
        <p>ELLIOT KIPNIS  Brooklyn, Aug. 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
